mention": "O2", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 264, "end": 266}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:36825"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "N3", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997805953025818, "span": {"begin": 269, "end": 271}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010710"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "phosphate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.998491644859314, "span": {"begin": 281, "end": 290}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:51307"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "diester", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9847379922866821, "span": {"begin": 292, "end": 299}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:32875"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "methyl", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996019005775452, "span": {"begin": 443, "end": 449}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:62801"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ethyl", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.998557984828949, "span": {"begin": 451, "end": 456}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:26308"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "propyl", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9985474944114685, "span": {"begin": 458, "end": 464}}], "text": "The event involves DNA alkylation to form a variety of different DNA adducts (i.e., alkylated nucleotides). Alkylation occurs at various sites in DNA and can include alkylation of adenine- Nl, - N3, - N7, guanine- N3, - O6, - N7, thymine-O2, - N3, - O4, cytosine- O2, -N3, and the phosphate (diester) group (reviewed in detail in Beranek 1990). In addition, alkylation can involve modification with different sizes of alkylation groups (e.g., methyl, ethyl, propyl). It should be noted that many of these adducts are not stable or are readily repaired (discussed in more detail below). A small proportion of adducts are stable and remain bound to DNA for long periods of time.", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:17:31 +0000 2026"}